<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-04-13T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-04-13T04:00:00-05:00" n="777" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d777">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 M Nielsen, Niels/2:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-04-13T17:00:00+08:00">April 13, 1933—5
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received April 13—7:47 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>324. Mukden’s April 12, 1 p.m. to the Department and the Legation.
                            Legation today received similar report from American Consul at Dairen
                            who added: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“Although Siuyen is not in the Kwantung leased territory, I have
                                    notified the Kwantung Government and police and informally
                                    requested such assistance as they may be in a position to
                                    render.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <p>Legation has informed Tokyo and Japanese Legation here.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>